liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: A stunning light display over Melbourne last night was most likely caused by remnants of a Russian rocket re-entering the atmosphere, Australia's space agency says. Here's the full statement from the Australian Space Agency: "The flashes of light seen across Melbourne skies overnight were likely the remnants of a Russian Soyuz-2 rocket re-entering the Earth's atmosphere. "Launch of the Soyuz-2 rocket occurred from Plesetsk Cosmodrome earlier in the evening. According to Russian authorities the launch placed a new generation 'GLONASS-K2' global navigation satellite into orbit. "This launch was notified and remnants of the rocket were planned to safely re-enter the atmosphere into the ocean off the south-east coast of Tasmania. "The Australian Space Agency will continue to monitor the outcomes of this re-entry with our Government partners."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Lights over Melbourne were likely caused by Russian rocket parts, authorities say

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Some sad news out of Italy this morning — a man has been crushed to death under thousands of wheels of a Parmesan-style hard cheese weighing about 40 kilograms each. Giacomo Chiapparini, 74, was buried under the cheeses when a shelf broke in his warehouse in the northern Lombardy region creating a domino effect which brought down thousands of wheels, firefighter Antonio Dusi from Bergamo tells AFP. It reportedly took 12 hours for rescuers to move the cheeses and wheels by hand to finally find Chiapparini. The warehouse, located in the small town of Romano di Lombardia near Bergamo, contained a total of 25,000 wheels of Grana Padano.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Italian man crushed to death by 40kg wheels of cheese

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Australian police arrested almost 160 people as part of a national crackdown on outlaw motorcycle gangs, which ran for a week and ended on Sunday. AAP reports that the country-wide operation, dubbed Taskforce Morpheus, led to almost 700 charges and seized 43 firearms, along with more than 20 other weapons, 11 vehicles and hundreds of thousands of dollars in cash. Officers also seized various quantities of different drugs during more than 70 raids across the country. "The success of this week of action should serve as a fresh warning to OMCG [outlaw motorcycle gang] members in Australia and those seeking to hideout offshore," national Taskforce Morpheus chair Detective Superintendent Anthony Conway says. "There is nowhere to run, and there is nowhere to hide."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Latest bikie crackdown leads to almost 700 charges

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: More and more economic data is showing the pull back in consumer spending because of the high cost of living. The Bureau of Statistics says household spending rose 1.8 per cent from June last year based on customer transactions from financial institutions. ABS head of business indicators Ben Dorber says it was the smallest rise in household spending since February 2021. "Spending on discretionary goods and services was down for the third straight month, falling 0.7 per cent over the year, as households adjust to cost of living pressures. “Non-discretionary spending rose 4.2 per cent, however the growth rate has been slowing since January, when it reached 21.0 per cent.” Spending on goods fell, while spending on services including child care, legal services and personal care rose. People spent more on staples like food, but less on non discretionary items like clothes and food.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Household spending continues to slow

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The West Australian government has announced it will overturn new Aboriginal cultural heritage laws, which were passed in 2021 after the destruction of sacred caves at Juukan Gorge in the Pilbara. The government will restore the original act from 1972 with "targeted, simple amendments" after an outcry from property owners over the new legislation. Under the new planned amendments, traditional owners will be able to appeal against development decisions under Section 18 of the 1972 act. Traditional owners were prohibited from appealing or talking publicly about Rio Tinto's plans to blow up the 46,000- year-old caves in 2020 under the old legislation. WA Premier Roger Cook says the new laws were too complicated and placed unnecessary burdens on property owners. "Today's announcement is about listening to the people of WA. "It' s about carefully considering the circumstances in front of us. "The Juukan Gorge tragedy was a global embarrassment for Australia, something needed to be done. "No-one can argue with that. "But our legislative response was wrong." Mr Cook rejected speculation that the WA government is repealing the laws to help the get the referendum on the Indigenous Voice to Parliament passed. "I have not had any communication with the prime minister or any federal members in relation to these laws." "The only contact I have had with the federal government in relation to these laws is when I contacted the prime minister yesterday to announce that we would be going in this direction." The Juukan Gorge traditional owners, the Puutu Kunti Kurrama and Pinikura Aboriginal Corporation, say they feel betrayed by the plans to repeal the new legislation. PKKP corporation chairman Terry Drage: “The previous heritage act, which predates Native Title, permitted the wanton destruction of  Juukan Gorge," he says. "While the new act is not perfect, it is better than what it replaced." “If the state government had listened to community feedback during the consultation phase, we  would not be in this mess." The PKKP has called on the federal government to proceed with national cultural heritage laws, as recommended by the parliamentary inquiry into the destruction of the Juukan Gorge caves. Mr Cook has ruled out "revisiting" new cultural heritage laws. Here's more from my colleague Keane Bourke in Perth.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: WA to repeal 2021 Aboriginal heritage laws

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: This morning's gains on the ASX 200 index have eased back over lunchtime in directionless trade. The ASX 200 index is up by 0.1 per cent with slightly more sectors higher than lower. Education firms and miners have eked out gains, but there are small falls among real estate and industrial firms. Building materials maker James Hardie has surged (+14.4 per cent) on a strong outlook for the US housing market. However, it warned that housing markets "remain uncertain". While sales fell, James Hardie says net adjusted income rose 13 per cent for the first quarter of the 2024 financial year. Coking coal miner Coronado Global Resources (-12 per cent) saw half-year profit fall by 65 per cent to $US199 million ($304 million) because of lower coal prices. The Australian dollar has slipped 0.4 per cent to 65.44 US cents on the higher greenback.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: ASX treads water
